Glad the earlier clarification helped. On the CPARS point, you’re exactly right that subcontractor performance can still be used effectively in OASIS+—the key is how well it’s documented. GSA understands that many firms, especially those that have historically operated as subs, won’t have a full CPARS portfolio. What they look for instead is strong, verifiable evidence that clearly demonstrates your role, scope, and impact.
Acceptable substitutes include: • Prime contractor letters confirming your work, responsibilities, and performance • COR/CO reference letters • Detailed project write‑ups that specify your contribution and outcomes
As long as the documentation is specific, attributable, and defensible, firms can still receive full credit even without CPARS.
