GSA understands that many firms (especially subs) don’t always have
CPARS. You can use subcontractor experience, as long as it’s well
documented. Instead of CPARS, GSA will look for strong supporting
evidence. Things like prime contractor letters, COR/CO references, or
detailed project write-ups that clearly show your role and the work you
performed. The key is making your contribution clear, specific, and
verifiable. If that’s done well, firms can still receive full credit
even without CPARS.

If GSA questions or lowers a self-score during validation, they
typically issue a clarification or evaluation notice. You’ll have a
chance to respond and provide additional support or explanation. The
turnaround is usually short (often a few days to about a week), so it’s
important to be ready with backup documentation. Your final score, and
pool eligibility, is based on that validated result, so the goal is to
get everything as tight and defensible as possible upfront.

Justin will be able to respond to any additional concerns you may have.
Thanks


